them.

44:44.115 --> 44:48.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Author Janna Levin is a
physicist and astronomer
at Barnard College. She's also
author of a

44:49.020 --> 44:52.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
novel, "A Madman Dreams of
Turing Machines."

44:52.156 --> 44:56.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the blues, we're sort of in
the realm
of metaphor here, but the idea
is to hear

44:56.594 --> 44:59.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the universe, at least as
aspects that we
can't possibly see.

45:00.031 --> 45:01.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANNA LEVIN, Author, "Black Hole
Blues and
Other Songs from Outer Space":
Yes, most of

45:01.432 --> 45:04.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
