They rang space-time
itself.

45:16.247 --> 45:17.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you have got
to be able
to hear them.

45:17.748 --> 45:20.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANNA LEVIN: Right. So, you have
to be able
to record the shape of the drum.

45:21.018 --> 45:24.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's basically what this
experiment
did. It recorded the shape of
the ringing

45:24.522 --> 45:28.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drum from two black holes that
collided 1.3
billion years ago.

45:28.259 --> 45:31.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, so
step back and
explain to us as simply as you
can, what is

45:31.629 --> 45:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a gravitational wave? And why is
it important
to our understanding of things?

45:36.500 --> 45:38.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JANNA LEVIN: Yes. Yes.

45:38.302 --> 45:40.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a gravitational wave is
really a ripple
or a change in the shape of
space and time

45:40.504 --> 45:44.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
itself. So, if you were floating
near these
colliding black holes, you would
literally

45:44.308 --> 45:49.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be squeezed and stretched. And
you would experience
this squeezing and stretching.
It emanates

45:49.447 --> 45:53.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from this collision. It causes
these ripples
in space, kind of like fish
swirling in a

45:53.618 --> 45:55.620 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pond causing water waves.

45:55.653 --> 45:58.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they emanate out. They
travel at
the speed of light, even though
they are not

45:58.990 --> 46:02.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
light. And eventually they make
it here to
the Earth. If you were floating
nearby, you

46:02.293 --> 46:05.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
might even literally hear the
wave, because
your ear could respond to the
vibrations.

46:06.030 --> 46:09.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you're
telling it through
the human drama. You have got
some really

46:09.867 --> 46:14.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
incredible characters, three of
them most
of all, who are at the
beginning. Tell us

46:14.538 --> 46:16.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a little bit about that.

46:16.273 --> 46:18.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANNA LEVIN: So, I really do
think it was
kind of a climbing Mount Everest
story, an

46:18.976 --> 46:20.711 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
adventure story.

46:20.745 --> 46:24.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People like Rai Weiss, who just
dreamed up
this idea of, how could you
record the shape

46:24.382 --> 46:28.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of space-time ringing? And it
was sort of
what he called a haiku, didn't
even believe

46:28.719 --> 46:31.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
anything real could come of it.
He started
this in the late '60s.

46:31.822 --> 46:36.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Later comes Kip Thorne, who is a
brilliant
theoretical astrophysicist. And
they kind

46:36.260 --> 46:41.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of pull resources. And
eventually Ron Drever
comes in. And now, after 50
years, there's

46:41.165 --> 46:43.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
800, 1,000 people working on
this campaign.

46:43.534 --> 46:46.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And they in a
sense sort of
bet their careers, right?

46:46.303 --> 46:50.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANNA LEVIN: At the time that
when people
like Rai and Kip were dreaming
about these

46:50.341 --> 46:53.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
things, people were not even
sure that black
holes were real.

46:53.878 --> 46:57.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there was a lot of argument
